title: For Sale:  Robinson Armament XCR-L (300 BO & 6.8 SPCII) w / Eotec & Magnifier
postcontent:
This is a Robinson Armament XCR-L in 300 Blackout and 6.8 SPCII with an Eotech XPS3 HWS and a G23 magnifier.  

This weapon system is all in like new condition and the 300 Black Out has been fired very few times and the 6.8 has not been fired at all.  This is my second XCR-L and they are awesome rifles for 3 gun or hunting since they make several different caliber conversions.  I personally wanted the 300 to shoot suppressed and the 6.8 for hunting purposes.  

This XCR-L comes in Field Dark Earth color with their new Keymod rail system. Side Charging Slide that remains in a fixed position when firing weapon. It is a piston operated system with each caliber having its own gas adjustment system.  The 300 Blackout is a 16" Barrel and very light weight with 1/7 twist and threaded.  The 6.8 is a 16" Barrel and is made heavier with 1/11 twist and threaded.  Has an excellent trigger system.  The Robinson Armament Fast Stock is Folding, extendable and has an adjustable cheek rest.  It comes with all manuals.  The rifle is easy to break down and clean and easy to reassemble.  Caliber changes are quick and easy.  Loosen one bolt located underneath where the barrel attaches to the upper and pull the barrel out, then open the upper and pull out the piston system and BCG.  Replace with the new bolt and piston and drop in the receiver.  Put in new barrel and tighten bolt.  Very easy and is a tac driver.  Rifle with both calibers is $2400.00

Eotech and magnifier will only be sold with the rifle at this price.  $600.00 for both the HWS and magnifier.  Both are in Field Dark Earth Color and match almost perfectly.  This is the Op Mod system from optics planet and cost $1100 new.

So can purchase rifle for $2400 and eotech for $600 - Total $3000.00

If you go online and try and order this system it will take months to get in your hands.  However, you can get optional caliber conversions from Robinson Arms website.

Best way to reach me is by text at REDACTED.  I will call back as soon as I can.  FTF transaction preferred but will ship through FFL.  I have hard case for both rifle and eotech.

title: For Sale:  Chinese Sks 7.62x39mm
postcontent:
Chinese marked Sks 
Bought from Tims Guns in Elbridge NY for 375+tax
Sweet rifle.  I removed all the cosmoline off all parts other than the stock by putting them in boiling water. 
Clean rifle that functions and shoots excellent.  Will send additional pictures of groups I shot with it and barrel machines markings.
The stock could be in better shape, but that doesn't effect the functioning of the rifle.
Stock is actually pretty neat, has foreign writing carved into it, and a thumb nail marking where one might dig their thumb into the stock during combat.

Chinese Sks were MILLED on the same machinery as Russian SKS.  Russian Sks are known for being the gold standard.  Russia sent Russian made tooling and mills to China and this Sks was produced on that machinery.  Vice yugo or other Sks which are stamped, more bulky and less stream lined.

this is a piece of history along with being a reliable, accurate rifle.
No flash suppressor or grenade launcher attachment and with the internal box magazine makes his rifle completely NYS legal.

title: For Sale:  Glock 19 G3 Heavily Upgraded
postcontent:
This Glock 19 is a Gen 3 model 9mm and while I can't tell you it's entire life story, I'm happy to tell you what I do know about it. 

It began its life as an everyday, off the shelf G19 in FDE. The original owner who purchased it decided a stock handgun was not good enough and proceeded to upgrade it. Here is a list of what I know has changed about it:

Titanium Nitride barrel ported at 15 degrees.
Titanium Nitride ejector and safety plunger.
Titanium Nitride stainless steel pins.
Pyramid adjustable trigger.
Pyramid extended magazine release.
Pyramid magazine baseplate.
Zev stainless steel guide rod.
Zev 18lb guide rod spring.
Zev spring kit.
Zev ghost trigger spring.
Trijicon hi-def front sight.
Williams adjustable rear sight.
Slide has had Raptor cuts to lessen the guns weight.
Trigger has been undercut to facilitate a better grip.
All internal parts have been mirror polished as well.

After the gun switched hands a couple times for whatever reasons (and I have to assume the fact that the FDE, TiN, and black just looked awful), it wound up in my hands.  I then had the trigger guard rounded over to fit my liking and also had the frame shot in a black Duracoat. The slide and extended magazine release (which was also TiN at one point) were then Cerakoted in a similar black to match.

The gun now looks very sharp and is a real head turner.  The gun comes with the original case, 2 magazines, and all original paperwork and accessories.  I'm not actively seeking trades but I do know this is a lot to swallow. I'd be glad to do a partial trade/cash if that helps the right person into such a great gun. 

My reasons for selling are that: 1. Not a Glock guy.  2. I know nothing about Glocks.  3.  I'm a .40 fan, not 9mm.  4.  It deserves to be used, not just sitting in a safe.  

Thanks for looking.

title: For Sale:  MGI Marck-15 Hydra 7.62x39 AK47 lower
postcontent:
modular m4 direct gas impingement platform with a replaceable mag-well.  Current configuration is for AK type magazines and ammunition.  16" Barrel with Yankee Hill LTA suppressor mount.

In my experience, it works with some drums and magazines, but is slightly finicky.  The MGI trigger group with extra strength Wolff hammer spring works fairly well, but aftermarked trigger groups such as the Geisselle SSA and AR-Gold triggers don't seem to have enough power to reliably ignite the primers on bulk steel cased ak ammo.  Strangely, they do run steel case Wolf 6.5 grendel ammo flawlessly.

The bolt and mags work fine with the cheap steel Wolf Grendel ammo, and with the modular upper you can swap barrels in seconds.  The Wolf Grendel ammo runs well in drums, especially, but better grade 6.5 ammo is loaded a bit longer, and tends to stick in the mags & drums.  

Currently configured with 45 degree offset iron sights.  

I have a stainless, nitrided, 18.5" fluted 6.5 grendel barrel also available for my cost of $275 that works with this setup as long as you're running the cheap steel case ammo.
